

TERA — Information Exchange in Non-Hermetic Systems

Abstract

In physical and informational systems, perfectly hermetic spaces rarely exist.
Any real system exchanges energy, signals, or information with its environment.

TERA models such systems as open dynamic spaces where stability emerges through controlled interaction between:

information

energy

temporal resonance


The framework describes how spaces exchange information through oscillation and damping, and how a control logic stabilizes these exchanges over time.


---

1. Hermetic vs Open Spaces

A perfectly hermetic system would satisfy

\dot{x}(t)=f(x(t))

meaning:

no external input

no energy exchange

no information flow


Such systems evolve only from their internal state.

However, real systems are open systems.

They are better described by

\dot{x}(t)=f(x(t),u(t),w(t))

where

 = external input

 = disturbance or environmental coupling


These terms represent energy and information exchange between spaces.


---

2. Two Interacting Spaces

TERA models interaction between two coupled spaces:

A(t) = \text{perception space}

B(t) = \text{model space}

The difference between them is

C(t)=B(t)-A(t)

This difference represents information drift.

If no stabilizing mechanism exists, then

\|C(t)\| \rightarrow \infty

or oscillates unpredictably.

Therefore the system requires stabilization.


---

3. Information Exchange as Oscillation

Information transfer between spaces can be modeled as oscillatory interaction.

For example

w(t)=a\sin(\omega t + \phi)

where

 = signal amplitude

 = frequency

 = phase


These oscillations represent the flow of energy and information across system boundaries.

In TERA this exchange is interpreted as resonance interaction between spaces.


---

4. Resonance and Dissipation

Every oscillatory interaction experiences damping.

Let

\chi_{dip}(\omega)

represent resonance dips in the system.

Then the effective system damping becomes

\varepsilon_{eff}(\omega)
=
\eta_0
(1-\chi_{dip}(\omega))

This quantity represents the effective viscosity of information exchange.

In other words:

resonance reduces dissipation

off-resonance interactions increase dissipation



---

5. Energy–Information Coupling

TERA links energy and information through resonance.

Conceptually:

E(p) \leftrightarrow f(p)

S(p) \leftrightarrow \Sigma(p)

meaning

energy determines signal amplitude

frequency determines information structure


Stability occurs when information exchange minimizes energy loss.


---

6. State Evolution

System states evolve through time according to

p_{n+1}
=
p_n
+
\Delta t
\left[
L(p_n)
+
m(k_n)\varepsilon_{eff}(n)
\right]

where

 = intrinsic system dynamics

 = control modulation

 = effective damping


This equation describes information-energy dynamics in open space.


---

7. Phase Quantization

TERA introduces a discrete phase representation.

The phase index is

k_n
=
\lfloor 9\theta_n / 2\pi \rfloor
\mod 9

This divides a circular phase space into nine sectors.

Geometrically this corresponds to a torus phase cycle.

This cycle acts as a temporal resonance clock.


---

8. Stability Function

To evaluate system stability we define

s(p)

which measures the system’s stress or instability.

The TERA root is defined as

\text{TERA Root}
=
\arg\min s(p)

This represents the state of minimal informational stress.


---

9. Gate Logic

TERA stabilizes the system using a discrete gate.

The rule is

ACCEPT  if s(p) < ε
WAIT    if ds/dt ≈ 0
REJECT  if s(p) ≥ ε

This gate acts as a bounded controller that regulates information flow.


---

10. Lyapunov Interpretation

Define a stability function

V(t)=\|C(t)\|^2

TERA attempts to enforce

\Delta V(t) \le 0

meaning that the difference between model and perception does not grow.

If

\Delta V(t) > 0

the gate intervenes.


---

11. Minimal TERA Equation

The conceptual core of the framework can be summarized as

\Delta S = Gate(I \cdot E \cdot \omega)

where

 = information

 = energy

 = temporal resonance


This equation expresses that state transitions are governed by the interaction of information, energy, and time.


---

12. Interpretation

TERA can therefore be interpreted as

> a stabilization logic for open systems that regulate information exchange through resonance, damping, and adaptive control.



The framework connects

open system dynamics

resonance physics

control theory

feedback stabilization



---

13. Conceptual Summary

TERA assumes that real spaces are never perfectly hermetic.

Instead, spaces exchange information through oscillatory interactions.

Stability arises when:

resonance aligns information transfer

damping limits uncontrolled drift

decision gates regulate state transitions


The result is a controlled evolution of information and energy across time.
